Introduction to the Differential Algebra Normal Form Algorithm using the Centrifugal Governor as an Example

Adrian Weisskopf111Michigan State University - Department of Physics and Astronomy — weisskop@msu.edu
Abstract

This paper provides a detailed introduction into the differential algebra (DA) based normal form algorithm using the example of the symplectic one dimensional system of the centrifugal governor. The intention of this paper is to make the single steps of the algorithm as clear as possible in the hope that the understanding and use of DA normal form methods are spread throughout the scientific community.

1 Introduction

This paper provides an example-driven walk-through of the differential algebra (DA) based normal form algorithm for a symplectic one dimensional (1D) system.

The DA framework was first developed to its current extent by Berz et al. [3, 1, 2]. It allows for an analytic/numeric-hybrid representation and manipulation of analytic functions in form of polynomial expansions. Taylor polynomials of order m𝑚m are represented by DA vectors which store the coefficients of the individual terms with floating point accuracy together with the order of the corresponding variables. Operations are defined on the DA vectors and implemented in the framework.

The DA normal form algorithm [3] is an advancement from the DA-Lie based version, the first arbitrary order algorithm by Forest, Berz, and Irwin [5]. The DA normal form algorithm yields a nonlinear change of phase space variables by an order-by-order transformation that significantly simplifies the representation to be rotational invariant up to the order of calculation. Thus, the resulting normal form representation, up to the order of calculation, constitutes circular motion with quasi-invariants as radii and only normal form phase space amplitude (and parameter) dependent angle advancements (see Fig. 1a+b).

The explanations on the DA normal form algorithm in this paper are based on Ref. [3], which also contains details on the calculation of the DA normal form algorithm for higher dimensional systems and other various special cases like non-symplectic systems. The appendix 5 yields a short summary on the main changes when considering higher dimensional phase space systems, e.g. resonances etc.

We start with an introduction to the centrifugal governor and the derivation of the equations of motion. This is followed by the calculation of an approximation of the flow of the equations of motions around an equilibrium position/point. This approximated flow is referred to as fixed point map. Given a linearly stable fixed point map, we go through the DA normal form algorithm step by step to obtain the rotationally invariant normal form map. The normal form is calculated up to third order. It will become obvious during the example that transformations of higher even and odd orders follow the same procedure as the second and third order transformation, respectively.

2 The centrifugal governor

The centrifugal governor is a device involving gravitational and centrifugal forces with the rotation axis parallel to the direction of the gravitational force. We are considering a mathematically idealized governor, which consists of two massless rods of equal length R𝑅R suspended at opposite sides of the rotation axis and a point mass m𝑚m attached at the end (opposite to where the rod is mounted) of each of the rods (see Fig. 1c). The angle between the rotation axis (in direction of gravitational pull) and the rod is denoted with the angle ϕitalic-ϕ\phi.

At a sufficiently high rotation frequency ω>ωm​i​n𝜔subscript𝜔𝑚𝑖𝑛\omega>\omega_{min} (see eq. 1) the centrifugal force Fc​e​n​tsubscript𝐹𝑐𝑒𝑛𝑡F_{cent} carries the masses radially outward, while the gravitational force Fg​r​a​vsubscript𝐹𝑔𝑟𝑎𝑣F_{grav} pulls down on them. The tension T𝑇T in the rods is given by the vector sum of the two forces. For every rotation frequency ω>ωm​i​n𝜔subscript𝜔𝑚𝑖𝑛\omega>\omega_{min}, there is an equilibrium angle ϕ0>0subscriptitalic-ϕ00\phi_{0}>0 (see subsection 2.1) where the gravitational and centrifugal forces balance.

A centrifugal governor is usually used in the application of a self-regulating mechanism, where the angle ϕitalic-ϕ\phi is negatively coupled back to the rotation frequency ω𝜔\omega through an extra mechanism (increase in ϕitalic-ϕ\phi ⇒⇒\Rightarrow decrease in ω𝜔\omega). Accordingly, in those applications, e.g. the steam engine, the rotation frequency ω𝜔\omega changes during the regulating process.

For the introduction to the normal form algorithm, we are considering the motion of the system with a fixed externally driven rotation frequency ω𝜔\omega. In particular, we are interested in the motion around the equilibrium position/angle ϕ0​(ω)subscriptitalic-ϕ0𝜔\phi_{0}\left(\omega\right) for a specific rotation frequency ω𝜔\omega. If the rods are perturbed from their equilibrium position/angle ϕ0​(ω)subscriptitalic-ϕ0𝜔\phi_{0}\left(\omega\right), they oscillate around ϕ0​(ω)subscriptitalic-ϕ0𝜔\phi_{0}\left(\omega\right) and we what to study the dynamics of that motion using the DA normal form algorithm.

For this specific example, the calculation of the fixed point map is straight forward from the flow and works for any time t𝑡t, since the equilibrium /fixed point does not change over time for a fixed ω𝜔\omega. 4 DA normal form algorithm

Before diving into the steps of the DA normal form algorithm we are clarifying the notation. The map is dependent on the ‘original’  variables (q0,p0)subscript𝑞0subscript𝑝0(q_{0},p_{0}). The transformations of the algorithm are done order-by-order. With each transformation, the index of the map and the variables is going to increase by 1, i.e. as a result of the first (order) transformation (the linear transformation) we get ℳ1subscriptℳ1\mathcal{M}_{1} dependent on the variables (q1,p1)subscript𝑞1subscript𝑝1(q_{1},p_{1}). Note that 𝒜m−1superscriptsubscript𝒜𝑚1\mathcal{A}_{m}^{-1} transforms (qm,pm)subscript𝑞𝑚subscript𝑝𝑚(q_{m},p_{m}) to (qm−1,pm−1)subscript𝑞𝑚1subscript𝑝𝑚1(q_{m-1},p_{m-1}), which are the variables of the map of the previous order ℳm−1subscriptℳ𝑚1\mathcal{M}_{m-1}. 𝒜msubscript𝒜𝑚\mathcal{A}_{m} transforms the intermediate result of ℳm−1∘𝒜m−1subscriptℳ𝑚1superscriptsubscript𝒜𝑚1\mathcal{M}_{m-1}\circ\mathcal{A}_{m}^{-1}, which is in the (qm−1,pm−1)subscript𝑞𝑚1subscript𝑝𝑚1(q_{m-1},p_{m-1})-phase space back to the new phase space in (qm,pm)subscript𝑞𝑚subscript𝑝𝑚(q_{m},p_{m}). 4.2 Linear transformation

The first order transformation is the diagonalization, transforming the system into the eigenvector space of the linear part ℒℒ\mathcal{L}. In order to determine the transformation 𝒜1subscript𝒜1\mathcal{A}_{1} and its inverse 𝒜1−1superscriptsubscript𝒜11\mathcal{A}_{1}^{-1} for the diagonalization, we determine the eigenvalues λ±subscript𝜆plus-or-minus\lambda_{\pm} and eigenvectors v→±subscript→𝑣plus-or-minus\vec{v}_{\pm} of the linear matrix L^^𝐿\hat{L} in the linear part ℒℒ\mathcal{L}. For this we require that all eigenvalues of ℳF​Psubscriptℳ𝐹𝑃\mathcal{M}_{FP} are distinct. Furthermore, we only consider cases where ℳF​Psubscriptℳ𝐹𝑃\mathcal{M}_{FP} is linearly stable, which means that all eigenvalues have an absolute value |λ|≤1𝜆1|\lambda|\leq 1. This also means that det(L^)≤1^𝐿1\det(\hat{L})\leq 1, otherwise at least one of the eigenvalues is larger than 1, making the system linearly unstable. Particularly interesting is the case det(L^)=1^𝐿1\det(\hat{L})=1, which indicates that the system is symplectic and only stable in the case of complex conjugate eigenvaluesλ±=e±i​μsubscript𝜆plus-or-minussuperscript𝑒plus-or-minus𝑖𝜇\lambda_{\pm}=e^{\pm i\mu}. While there are procedures for the cases of real and degenerate eigenvalues with magnitude smaller than one (see Ref. [3]), this work only illustrates the procedures for the most relevant and common symplectic case of only complex conjugate eigenvalues and eigenvectors.

4.3 Nonlinear transformations

The nonlinear transformations are the key part of the normal form algorithm. In this first part of this subsection we are going look at an m𝑚mth order transformation in general, before going through the nonlinear transformation for order two and three in detail. Don’t get discouraged from reading further if the general notation is a bit overwhelming.
